// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
// Shared discourse pieces
// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

# uncertain-source
- I heard
- Someone told me
- A dockworker claims
- The morning bulletin says
- My neighbour insists
- A courier mentioned
- The queue at customs was talking about how
- The night shift keeps saying
- A passenger swears
- The local channel reported

# rumour-ending
- Probably just station gossip.
- I wouldn't repeat that near security.
- Make of that what you will.
- I don't believe it, but I did lock my door.
- Nobody seems eager to confirm it.
- That is all anyone will tell me.
- It sounds ridiculous, which is why I half believe it.
- I suppose stranger things happen out here.
- The official notice says otherwise, naturally.
- You didn't hear it from me.

# mild-ending
- Nobody seems worried.
- Maybe it has always been like that.
- I have learned not to ask.
- That is station life, I suppose.
- Management calls it normal wear.
- It could be worse.
- At least it makes the shift interesting.
- Apparently that is within regulations.
- Someone will probably fix it eventually.
- I am trying not to think about it.
- People here barely notice anymore.
- There is probably a form for it.

# annoyed-ending
- Again.
- As usual.
- Nobody bothered to warn me.
- That was not in the brochure.
- I could have stayed home for this.
- Somehow this is my problem now.
- The supervisor says it is temporary.
- I have stopped expecting an explanation.
- And they wonder why people complain.
- I am adding it to the list.

# friendly-question
- How's your day going, friend?
- Has the station been treating you well?
- You waiting for a shuttle too?
- Know anywhere quiet to sit?
- Is it always this busy around here?
- Have you been stationed here long?
- You look like you know your way around.
- Any idea where they keep the decent coffee?
- Are all the lifts this slow?
- First time this far from the inner worlds?

# personal-reaction
- I could use a quiet hour.
- I should probably get back to work.
- I am starting to miss planets.
- I need another cup of coffee.
- I suppose I will get used to it.
- I am too tired to be surprised.
- I might take the long way home.
- I should have stayed in my cabin.
- I will worry about it after my shift.
- I promised myself I would stop complaining.

# recent-time
- this morning
- during the last shift
- just after the lights dimmed
- before breakfast
- around the middle of station night
- when the freighter docked
- during the power test
- less than an hour ago
- while customs was changing shifts
- after the final shuttle arrived

# long-time
- since yesterday morning
- for three station cycles
- since the last maintenance inspection
- for most of the week
- ever since I arrived
- since the old supervisor retired
- for longer than anyone admits
- since docking ring four reopened
- since the last software update
- since the festival ended

