# component-failure
- shut itself off
- emitted a cloud of steam
- displayed every warning at once
- began running backwards
- locked three people in a corridor
- sprayed coolant across the floor
- started speaking in another language
- reported itself missing
- tripped the local power bus
- opened when it should have closed

# station-event
- a shuttle docks
- the lights dim
- the station changes shift
- someone uses the central lift
- the reactor output rises
- the public channel updates
- a freighter enters the ring
- the kitchen starts breakfast

# component-behaviour
- resets itself
- makes @maintenance-sound
- displays an old error code
- loses power
- reports a pressure fault
- flashes blue
- locks for exactly twelve seconds
- smells faintly burnt
- triggers a maintenance announcement
- vibrates through the floor

# component-evidence
- puddle underneath it
- smell in the corridor
- noise behind the wall
- scorch mark above it
- queue forming beside it
- technician sleeping beneath it
- collection of loose screws nearby
- handwritten warning taped to it

# maintenance-reaction
- Maintenance arrived, looked at it, and left.
- The corridor was closed for the rest of the shift.
- Someone put a chair over the puddle.
- The official report called it “minor.”
- It started working again before anyone touched it.
- The nearest technician pretended not to see.
- We all took the long route after that.
- The repair estimate is apparently confidential.
- At least the alarms still work.
- That is how I learned where the emergency stairs are.

# maintenance-noise-line
- There is @maintenance-sound coming from @maintenance-location. @noise-reaction
- The @station-component makes @maintenance-sound whenever @station-event. @noise-reaction
- I heard @maintenance-sound behind my cabin wall @recent-time. @noise-reaction
- Maintenance says @maintenance-sound is only thermal expansion. I do not find that comforting.
- If you hear @maintenance-sound near @station-place, walk the other way.

# maintenance-sound
- a slow metallic knocking
- three precise chimes
- a grinding noise
- something like distant coughing
- an expensive sort of rattle
- a high electrical whine
- a rhythm almost like footsteps
- a wet mechanical clicking
- an occasional heavy thump
- a sound like coins in a dryer
- a low vibration
- a brief burst of static
- a fan repeatedly trying to start
- a noise like bending glass
- an alarm too quiet to be useful

# maintenance-location
- behind the eastern pressure wall
- beneath docking ring four
- somewhere above the market
- inside the central lift shaft
- under the hydroponics floor
- beyond a sealed service hatch
- behind the customs office
- in the old ventilation trunk
- near the reactor access corridor
- inside the waste-processing wall

# noise-reaction
- Nobody else admits they can hear it.
- It stops whenever a technician arrives.
- I have started timing it.
- The night shift says it is harmless.
- It kept me awake for two cycles.
- The station map shows nothing there.
- It is getting louder.
- I preferred it when the alarms worked.
- My neighbour thinks it is music.
- The official advice is to ignore it.

# maintenance-repair-line
- They fixed @broken-thing with @improvised-fix. It seems to be holding.
- I watched @maintenance-worker spend @repair-duration repairing @broken-thing. The problem was @simple-fault.
- The replacement for @broken-thing arrived, but it was meant for @wrong-station-part.
- According to @maintenance-worker, @broken-thing needs @rare-part. The next shipment is @part-delay.
- Someone repaired @broken-thing using a part from @salvage-source. @mild-ending

